<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp2sec3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Linear Diophantine Equations</title>

  <p> </p>

  <definition xml:id="definition-linear_diophantine_equation">
    <title>Linear Diophantine Equation</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A <term>linear Diophantine equation</term> is an equation of the form <m>ax + by = c</m>, where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are integers and the <term>solutions</term> <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are required to be integers.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-solvability_of_linear_diophantine_equations">
  <title>Solvability of Linear Diophantine Equations</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Given integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, the linear Diophantine equation <m>ax + by = c</m> has a solution if and only if <m>\gcd(a,b) \mid c</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  For the forward direction, assume that there is a solution <m>(x,y)</m> to the equation.  Show that <m>\gcd(a,b) \mid c</m>.  For the reverse direction, assume that <m>\gcd(a,b) \mid c</m>.  Show that there is a solution to the equation.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/>,   <xref ref="definition-gcd"/>, <xref ref="proposition-divisibility_of_linear_combination"/>, and <xref ref="proposition-bezout_identity"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>



<proposition xml:id="proposition-solvability_of_linear_diophantine_equations_unit">
  <title>Solvability of Linear Diophantine Equations (Unit Case)</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Given integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, the linear Diophantine equation <m>ax + by = 1</m> has a solution if and only if <m>\gcd(a,b) = 1</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  You may find <xref ref="proposition-solvability_of_linear_diophantine_equations"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

  <definition xml:id="definition-relatively_prime">
    <title>Relatively Prime</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Two integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are <term>relatively prime</term> if <m>\gcd(a,b) = 1</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <proposition xml:id="proposition-dividing_to_get_relatively_prime">
    <title>Dividing to Get Relatively Prime</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If <m>a,b\in \Z</m> and <m>d = \gcd(a,b)</m>, then <m>a/d</m> and <m>b/d</m> are relatively prime.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Try a direct proof.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-gcd"/>, <xref ref="proposition-solvability_of_linear_diophantine_equations"/>, <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/>,  <xref ref="definition-commutative_ring"/>, <xref ref="definition-relatively_prime"/>, and <xref ref="proposition-solvability_of_linear_diophantine_equations_unit"/> useful.
        </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <p>
    Given a particular solution to a linear Diophantine equation, we can find all solutions.
  </p>


  <proposition xml:id="proposition-the_general_solution_to_a_linear_diophantine_equation">
    <title>The General Solution to a Linear Diophantine Equation</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If <m>a,b\in \Z</m> are nonzero, <m>c\in \Z</m>, and <m>x_0,y_0\in \Z</m> are a particular solution to the equation <m>ax + by = c</m>, then all solutions are given by 
            <md>x = x_0 + \left(\frac{b}{d}\right)t, \quad y = y_0 - \left(\frac{a}{d}\right)t</md>
            where <m>t</m> runs through the integers and <m>d = \gcd(a,b)</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Try a direct proof.  You must show two things: (1) that every solution has the form given, and (2) that every point of the given form is a solution.  Start with (1).  Suppose that <m>(x_1, y_1)</m> is another solution.  Then <m>ax_1 + by_1 = c</m>.  Subtracting the original equation <m>ax_0 + by_0 = c</m> gives <m>a(x_1 - x_0) + b(y_1 - y_0) = 0</m>.  This means <m>a(x_1 - x_0) = -b(y_1 - y_0)</m>.  Since <m>\gcd(a,b) = d</m>, we can write <m>a = da'</m> and <m>b = db'</m> for some integers <m>a'</m> and <m>b'</m>.  Show that <m>b' \mid (x_1 - x_0)</m> (why???).  Deduce there exists an integer <m>t</m> such that <m>x_1 - x_0 = tb'</m>, and hence <m>y_1 - y_0 = -ta'</m>.  
        </p>
        <p>
            Now show (2).  Let <m>t\in \Z</m>.  Show that <m>x_1 = x_0 + \left(\frac{b}{d}\right)t</m> and <m>y = y_0 - \left(\frac{a}{d}\right)t</m> is a solution. Analyze <m>ax_1 + by_1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            You may find  <xref ref="definition-linear_diophantine_equation"/>, <xref ref="definition-commutative_ring"/>, <xref ref="definition-relatively_prime"/>, <xref ref="definition-gcd"/>, <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/>, <xref ref="proposition-solvability_of_linear_diophantine_equations"/>,  and <xref ref="proposition-solvability_of_linear_diophantine_equations_unit"/> useful.
        </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <activity xml:id="activity-general_solution_to_a_linear_diophantine_equation">
  <title>Computing the general solution to a Linear Diophantine Equation</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the general solution to the linear Diophantine equation <m>5x+6y=100</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
</activity>

</section>